children.subject: I'm only taking 2 CS courses next semester, all I need to graduate. Good to know 161 has much higher workload than 188 though..both interesting, but 161 probably better for Software Engineering

Whoops, missed that part. 161+162 is probably the most relevant for software engineering out of all the courses on that list.

I've heard that 169 is stuff you'll be doing in a full time job, while 160 is already full.
Ya i'm pretty set on 162 and 161, thanks Anon :)

I would be cautious about taking 189, 162, and 161 in the same semester.

For reference, I took 189 with prof sahai, 162, and 188 with no other commitments, and it was a tough semester. IMO 161 has a much higher workload than 188.

history.content: Given that you haven't taken ee126/127 and you having an already heavy workload with 161+162, I'd suggest you to take ee127 (would fit your schedule well without being too time consuming and prepare you for 189 at the same time).

children.subject:
Fair enough, strongly advise you to not add 189 into your schedule then. And please drop it soon so interested students can enroll.
Also if you want a light upperdiv, 188 will fit in well but might not be super useful for industry as such; nevertheless, it is a fun and interesting class, especially in your last semester

Good point, i'll un-enroll in 189 asap. Can you explain why it prepares well for 189, and possibly ML in general?

I lowkey want to self study 162 and 161, and just take EECS 126 and EECS 127 lol.

For Student Answer:

Next semester will be my last, and i don't think I will take 162, 161, and EECS 127. I also have very poor Stats/Linear Algebra skills so I don't know if EECS 127 + CS 162 will be too much. I only plan on taking 2 courses since that's all I need to graduate. I might take another easy one if last semester financial aid requires 13 units.

history.content:
(Currently Enrolled in: 162, 161, 189)

Hey everyone,

I'm going to pick 2 of these. Here are my goals:

1. Have a foundation of Software Engineering after graduating(hence 161, 162)

2. Have better maturity in Stats and Linear Algebra(hence 110, 134, don't want to rush into ML by taking 126, 127, or 189...although I could. Haven't taken 16B, I took Math 54 equivalent in middle school lol, only stats background is CS 70)

3. Have a chill semester(hence tech electives or easier schedule)

I'm leaning towards 161 and 162. I would just have to study ML from the very beginning of Linear Algebra and Stats if I want to get into the field, which could be tougher than self studying 162 and 161.

Here are the courses:

CS 152 -Asanovic

CS 160 -Hartmann

CS 161 -Popa

CS 162 -Kubiatowicz

CS 169 -Fox

CS 188 -Levine, Russell

CS 189 -Shewchuk

EECS 126 -Ramchandran

EECS 127 -Ashaolu

Math 110 -Holtz

Stat 134 -Lucas

Also, if anyone has tech elective suggestions that are chill, I can add them onto this list. Secondly, I might go crazy and take 189 and 162 together ;)
